Window functions
A window function performs a calculation across a set of rows related to the current row, without grouping them into a single result.
Unlike GROUP BY, it does NOT reduce rows — it keeps all rows and adds extra calculated values.
GROUP BY → combines rows → gives 1 result per group
Window Function → keeps all rows → adds extra info per row
Syntax:
FUNCTION_NAME() OVER (
    PARTITION BY column
    ORDER BY column
)

Example
| id | name | dept | salary |
| -- | ---- | ---- | ------ |
| 1  | A    | IT   | 50000  |
| 2  | B    | IT   | 60000  |
| 3  | C    | HR   | 40000  |
| 4  | D    | HR   | 45000  |
| 5  | E    | IT   | 70000  |
ROW_NUMBER() : Assigns a unique number to each row
  SELECT name, dept, salary,
       ROW_NUMBER() OVER (ORDER BY salary DESC) AS row_num
  FROM employees;

RANK(): Ranks rows but skips numbers if tie
  SELECT name, salary,
       RANK() OVER (ORDER BY salary DESC) AS rank
  FROM employees;
If two people have same salary:

DENSE_RANK(): Similar to rank but no gaps
SELECT name, salary,
       DENSE_RANK() OVER (ORDER BY salary DESC) AS rank
FROM employees;

PARTITION BY (Grouping inside window): Works like GROUP BY, but keeps rows
SELECT name, dept, salary,
       ROW_NUMBER() OVER (PARTITION BY dept ORDER BY salary DESC) AS rank
FROM employees;

SUM() as Window Function: Calculates running total
SELECT name, salary,
       SUM(salary) OVER (ORDER BY salary) AS running_total
FROM employees;

AVG() (Average per department)
SELECT name, dept, salary,
       AVG(salary) OVER (PARTITION BY dept) AS avg_salary
FROM employees;

LAG() (Previous Row Value)
SELECT name, salary,
       LAG(salary) OVER (ORDER BY salary) AS prev_salary
FROM employees;

LEAD() (Next Row Value)
SELECT name, salary,
       LEAD(salary) OVER (ORDER BY salary) AS next_salary
FROM employees;

Date and Time functions
These functions help you:
Get current date/time
Extract parts (year, month, day)
Add/subtract dates
Format dates
SQL stores date like:
'2026-04-10 14:30:00'
CURRENT DATE and TIME
Get current date : SELECT CURRENT_DATE;
Get current time : SELECT CURRENT_TIME;
Get current date & time: SELECT NOW();

EXTRACT (Get specific part)
Extract year: SELECT EXTRACT(YEAR FROM '2026-04-10');
Extract month: SELECT EXTRACT(MONTH FROM '2026-04-10');
Extract day: SELECT EXTRACT(DAY FROM '2026-04-10');

Some DB's like mysql use this
SELECT YEAR('2026-04-10');
SELECT MONTH('2026-04-10');
SELECT DAY('2026-04-10');

DATE ADD / SUBTRACT
Add days : SELECT DATE_ADD('2026-04-10', INTERVAL 5 DAY);
Subtract days: SELECT DATE_SUB('2026-04-10', INTERVAL 3 DAY);
DATEDIFF (Difference between dates): SELECT DATEDIFF('2026-04-10', '2026-04-01');

FORMAT DATE
SELECT DATE_FORMAT('2026-04-10', '%d-%m-%Y');

LAST DAY OF MONTH: SELECT LAST_DAY('2026-04-10');
DAY NAME / MONTH NAME 
SELECT DAYNAME('2026-04-10');   -- Friday
SELECT MONTHNAME('2026-04-10'); -- April

NOW vs SYSDATE
SELECT NOW();
SELECT SYSDATE();
NOW() → same value in one query
SYSDATE() → real-time changing

NUMERIC FUNCTIONS
Numeric functions are used to:
Perform mathematical calculations
ABS() → Absolute Value : SELECT ABS(-10);
CEIL() / CEILING() → Round Up : SELECT CEIL(4.2);
FLOOR() → Round Down : SELECT FLOOR(4.8);
ROUND() → Round to nearest value : SELECT ROUND(12.345, 2); output: 12.35, Without decimal places: SELECT ROUND(12.6); output: 13
TRUNCATE() → Cut decimal (no rounding): SELECT TRUNCATE(12.987, 2);
MOD() → Remainder : SELECT MOD(10, 3);
POWER() → Exponent: SELECT POWER(2, 3);
SQRT() → Square Root: SELECT SQRT(16);
RAND() → Random Number: SELECT RAND();
SIGN() → Check sign : SELECT SIGN(-15);

